2.13 Show that the lowest value taken by the function 3x4 +4x3 −12x2 +6 is −26.
We need to calculate the ﬁrst and second derivatives of the function in order to establish the positions and natures of its turning points:
y(x) = 3x4 + 4x3 − 12x2 + 6, y (x) = 12x3 + 12x2 − 24x, y (x) = 36x2 + 24x − 24.
Setting y (x) = 0 gives x(x + 2)(x − 1) = 0 with roots 0, 1 and −2. The corresponding values of y (x) are −24, 36 and 72. Since y(±∞) = ∞, the lowest value of y is that corresponding to the lowest minimum, which can only be at x = 1 or x = −2, as y must be positive at a minimum. The values of y(x) at these two points are y(1) = 1 and y(−2) = −26, and so the lowest value taken is −26.
