same as the corresponding terms in the expansion of (z − 1)4; only the constant term needs correction. Thus, we may write the original equation as
0 = f(z) = (z3 − 2)[(z − 1)4 − 3], with solutions z = 21/3e2nπi/3 n = 0, 1, 2 or
z − 1 = 31/4e2nπi/4 n = 0, 1, 2, 3. The seven roots are therefore
√ 21/3, 21/3 −1 ± i 3 , 1 ± 31/4, 1 ± 31/4i.
2 As is to be expected, each root that has a non-zero imaginary part occurs as one of a complex conjugate pair.
