4.35 One of the factors contributing to the high relative permittivity of water

to static electric ﬁelds is the permanent electric dipole moment, p, of the water

molecule. In an external ﬁeld E the dipoles tend to line up with the ﬁeld, but

they do not do so completely because of thermal agitation corresponding to the

temperature, T , of the water. A classical (non-quantum) calculation using the

Boltzmann distribution shows that the average polarisability per molecule, α, is

